    "answer": "We are given that $5n \\equiv 1 \\pmod{29}$. This means that $5n$ is congruent to $1$ modulo $29$, or that $5n$ divided by $29$ leaves a remainder of $1$.\n\nTo find the value of $n$, we can multiply both sides of the congruence by the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$. The modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$ is the integer $x$ such that $5x \\equiv 1 \\pmod{29}$. We can find this value by using the extended Euclidean algorithm.\n\nThe extended Euclidean algorithm is a method for finding the greatest common divisor of two integers, as well as the coefficients of B\u00e9zout's identity, which is the equation $ax + by = \\gcd(a, b)$ for some integers $x$ and $y$. In this case, we want to find the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$, so we will use the extended Euclidean algorithm to find the coefficients of B\u00e9zout's identity for $5$ and $29$.\n\nWe have:\n\n\\begin{align*}\n29 &= 5(5) + 4\\\\\n5 &= 4(1) + 1\\\\\n4 &= 1(4) + 0\n\\end{align*}\n\nNow we can work backwards to find the coefficients of B\u00e9zout's identity:\n\n\\begin{align*}\n1 &= 5 - 4(1)\\\\\n&= 5 - (29 - 5(5))(1)\\\\\n&= 5(6) - 29(1)\n\\end{align*}\n\nTherefore, the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$ is $6$, since $5(6) \\equiv 1 \\pmod{29}$.\n\nNow that we have the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$, we can multiply both sides of the congruence $5n \\equiv 1 \\pmod{29}$ by $6$ to get:\n\n\\begin{align*}\n6(5n) &\\equiv 6(1) \\pmod{29}\\\\\n\\Rightarrow\\qquad n &\\equiv 6 \\pmod{29}\n\\end{align*}\n\nTherefore, the value of $n$ is $6$.\n\nNow we can find the value of $\\left(2^n\\right)^3 - 3 \\pmod{29}$. We have:\n\n\\begin{align*}\n\\left(2^6\\right)^3 - 3 &\\equiv 2^{18} - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv (2^2)^9 - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv 4^9 - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv (4^2)^4 \\cdot 4 - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv 16^4 \\cdot 4 - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv (-13)^4 \\cdot 4 - 3 \\pmod{29}\\\\\n&\\equiv (-13