\\\n5 &= 4(1) + 1\\\\\\\\\\n4 &= 1(4) + 0\\n\\\\end{align*}\\n\\nNow we can work backwards to find the coefficients of B\u00e9zout's identity:\\n\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n1 &= 5 - 4(1)\\\\\\\\\\n&= 5 - (29 - 5(5))(1)\\\\\\\\\\n&= 5(6) - 29(1)\\n\\\\end{align*}\\n\\nTherefore, the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$ is $6$, since $5(6) \\\\equiv 1 \\\\pmod{29}$.\\n\\nNow that we have the modular multiplicative inverse of $5$ modulo $29$, we can multiply both sides of the congruence $5n \\\\equiv 1 \\\\pmod{29}$ by $6$ to get:\\n\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n6(5n) &\\\\equiv 6(1) \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\Rightarrow\\\\qquad n &\\\\equiv 6 \\\\pmod{29}\\n\\\\end{align*}\\n\\nTherefore, the value of $n$ is $6$.\\n\\nNow we can find the value of $\\\\left(2^n\\\\right)^3 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}$. We have:\\n\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n\\\\left(2^6\\\\right)^3 - 3 &\\\\equiv 2^{18} - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (2^2)^9 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv 4^9 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (4^2)^4 \\\\cdot 4 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv 16^4 \\\\cdot 4 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)^4 \\\\cdot 4 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)^3 \\\\cdot 4 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-13) \\\\cdot 4 - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-13)(4) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-13)(-4) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(4(-4)) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod{29}\\\\\\\\\\n&\\\\equiv (-13)(-13)(-13)(-16) - 3 \\\\pmod